{"questionId":"22585","questionHtml":"<p>Hence find <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> as a function of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>∫</mo><mi>B</mi><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mtext> </mtext><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mtext>e</mtext><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>C</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong><br>Note:</strong> The first constant must be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>, and the second can be any constant for the final&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em> to be awarded. Accept a change of constant applied at the end.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22585","referenceCode":"21N.3.AHL.TZ0.2b.iii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence find y as a function of t.","paper":"3","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"b.iii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.14—Implicit functions, related rates, optimisation","Topic 5 —Calculus","AHL 5.18—1st order DE’s – Euler method, variables separable, integrating factor, h